REPL Commands (type after starting --repl)
Angles are motor-shaft degrees. Moves block until finished.

help
Show this help list.

status
Print current angles and tuning:

both <deg>
Move both motors to the same absolute angle.
Example: both 15

m1 <deg>
Move Motor 1 to an absolute angle (Motor 2 stays).
Example: m1 30

m2 <deg>
Move Motor 2 to an absolute angle (Motor 1 stays).
Example: m2 -10

jog m1 <±deg> / jog m2 <±deg>
Relative nudges.
Examples: jog m1 +5, jog m2 -3

speed <deg/s>
Set max speed. Example: speed 240

accel <deg/s^2>
Set acceleration. Example: accel 1500

shape <num>
Accel curve shape:

< 1.0 = snappier early acceleration

1.0 = linear

> 1.0 = softer start
Example: shape 0.5

quit (or exit, q)
Exit the REPL.

Tip: Use REPL for sequences because angles persist while the REPL runs.

CLI Flags (one-shot)
All angles are absolute (session-absolute; start at 0°/0° each run).

--gears <deg>
Move both motors to the same absolute angle.

--m1 <deg> / --m2 <deg>
Set each motor’s absolute angle. If you provide only one, the other holds its current value.

--speed <deg/s>
Max speed (motor-shaft deg/s).

--accel <deg/s^2>
Acceleration.

--shape <num>
Accel curve shape (snappier ↔ softer).

--spr <steps>
Steps per revolution (default 200 for a 1.8° stepper).

--micro <steps>
Microstepping (e.g., 16) — match your driver DIP.

--invert2 / --no-invert2
Invert Motor 2’s logical direction (default is inverted).

--disable-on-exit
Drop ENA on exit (de-energize). By default motors stay enabled to hold position.
